data.content:
This is a known **C# 14 overload resolution breaking change** with span parameters.

## What happened

In C# 14, `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overloads now participate in type inference and extension method resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (a span-based method) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Since `MemoryExtensions.Contains` cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree, it throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Any of these three options work — force the call to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<T>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the compiler from picking the span overload, keeping the expression tree valid.
